We hate to be the bearer of bad newsbut your sushi and seaweed snacks are breaking you outWe ve said it before and we will say it againiodide rich foods are not a friend to the acne proneSeaweed and kelp in particular have some of the highest iodide content found in any food with a 1020 ppm countThis is ten times more iodide than iodized salt which also triggers acneKeep this in mind when planning your next dinner date or browsing the snack aisleThe foods you eat today will haunt your skin for days to come

Do you know that Korean seaweed is famous because it is deliciousIt s really delicious if you eat it with riceOf courseit s tasty to eat just like a snackThe seaweed I brought here is not like the seaweed you ve ever eatenThis is a premium traditional roasted seaweed that is hand baked one by one in the traditional korean way at hot stoneusing a very best high quality korean perilla oil and saltThere are four kinds of seaweedstraditionalgarlicspicyand WasabiIt s really different from the seaweed in the marketIt s delicious and premium There are 6 kinds of roasted seaweed snacks withOrignal flavorShrimpWasabiCurrySpicy Anchovy and Nuts flavorIt s premium seaweed snackwhich is not salty using natural ingredients and is nutritiousNever using chemical seasoningSoI chose ittasted itand found it hardI visited a local factory twice in November of last year and January of this yearI checked it out and tasted it and brought it to singapore after a lot of meetingsNow Go to Culina in Dempseyculinacomodempsey and ask for samples to tasteIf you taste ityou ll definitely fall in love with it1811144 6 culinacomodempseyculinacomodempsey

Not SkincarebutTextureTuesday with FOODKorean Han Bugakcourtesy of0 8L USA Bugak describes a Korean traditional snack and I received 3 bags of these crispy treats Pumpkin LaverseaweedandHot Chili Pepper These are made in YeongjuSobaek MountainSouth Korea and almost all of the ingredients are harvested from this clean regionThese snacks do not contain any artificial flavors or food additives and rely on the veggies pure raw cane sugar and salicornia herbacea saltwhich is a salt that contains salicorniaa marshland plant that contains ironcalciumtaurine and other rich mineralsTasting Time The first one I tried was the hot pepper this is SO good It is a little bit spicybecause some of the pepper pieces still have the seedswhich are the hottest part of the pepper I don t know if these are baked or friedbut they are so crispy but very light and the coating of sugar salt helps balance the bitterness of the pepper Next up pumpkin These are more like chips and don t melt in your mouth like the pepper but they have a great crunch to them This one was more sweet with a touch of salt Of courseI ate this bag in one sitting hahahaLast was the Laver NowI have had seaweed crunches beforeand I do love themHoweverthis one really had the taste of the ocean with it I found it to be overpowering in a bad way I didn t eat these by themselves insteadI crushed them up and sprinkled them on dishes to help cut down on the seaweedy taste They were ALMOST therebut it s like they weren t rinsed enough I really loved the Hot Pepper Pumpkin flavors and I noticed they have otherslike potatocarrot burdock I would love to try them all prsampleunboxingbeauty kfoodfoodpornpumpkinkoreansnackssnackscrispysnackKoreanfoodvegetariankoreansnackbugakHanBuGakPumkinHotPepperLaverhealthysnackvegan08liter08Lreviewfoodreviewkfoodkoreanfoodsnacks

Mermaids bladderHas a ring to it NereocystisGreek formermaid s bladder is a monotypic genus of kelp containing the species Nereocystis luetkeanaSome common names include edible kelpbull kelpbullwhip kelpribbon kelpbladder wrackand variations of these namesIt forms thick beds on rocksand is an important part of kelp forestsIt can grow to a maximum of 36 m118 ft Nereocystis has a holdfast of about 40 cm16 in and a single stipetopped with a pneumatocyst containing carbon monoxidefrom which sprout the numerousabout 30 64bladesThe blades may be up to 4 m13 ftlongand up to 15 cm5 9 inwideIt is usually annualsometimes persisting up to 18 monthsNereocystis is the only kelp which will drop spore patchesso that the right concentration of spores lands near the parent s holdfastIt is common along the Pacific Coast of North Americafrom Southern California to the Aleutian IslandsAlaskawikipedia

Throughout history people have flocked to coastal areas for foodForaging for food can be rewarding here Even if I don t catch any fish I often forage for seaweed when I m on the coast I normally use it as an ingredient with pasta either blanched or friedLast time I wanted to do something else with it so I made chips out of it It s very easy to make and it tastes greatSeaweed contains a high amount of iodine which can be healthy for youMany people suffer from iodine deficiency so in that sense it can be very beneficialJust make sure you don t eat too much of it too oftenThe high amount of iodine can cause iodine poisoningAnd beware not to eat it at all if you have Metabolic disorderThat said it also contains both vitamins ABCE and K as well a big variety of mineralsamino acids and omega 3s If you want to try making seaweed chips here s an easy recipe for you The only ingredients you need areSeaweedVirgin olive oil and Sea saltStart by cutting the top shoots into bite sized piecesPour a few spoons of virgin olive oil in a bowltoss the seaweed around in it and add some sea salt to itTake out the seaweed and let the oil drip off before you spread it out on a baking trayPut it in a preheated oven at 100 degrees C for about an hour and voil  scandinavia

What is SeaweedSeaweedsa marine form of algaeare found in all the earth s oceanin all climate zones from the warm seas of the tropics to the cold waters of the Arctic and Antarcticyet they remain something of a mysteryThe global distribution of seaweeds has not been comprehensively mappedthe full details of their habitats are unknowntheir taxonomic classification is incomplete and their biodiversity is not yet understoodBut there are reckoned to be about 10 000 kinds of seaweed in the worldand they are essential to the life of the planetAlthough we think the oxygen we breathe comes from land plantsmarine algae of all sizes provide some 75 percent of the planet s oxygen supply through photosynthesisand absorb a huge amount of atmospheric carbon dioxideAnd as noted by Darwinseaweeds play a foundation role in marine ecosystemsproviding food and shelter for many marine organisms and for the people and animals that live on themSee Global Seaweed NetworkNatural History Museumwww nhm ac ukThe Aquatic Biomewww ucmp berkeley eduwww microbeworld  oasis

A Letter from OMG Founders A warm welcomeThe story of HEASAN SEAWEED Lifestyle Culture began here in Seoulour home town in South KoreaWe are two sisters Chiwon and Eunseo who developed a passion for seaweed way back in our childhoodOne thing we will never forget is the story mum would tell us about how the ocean whale would always eat seaweed after giving birth to renew her energy and be sure that her milk is full of the right nutrients for her youngIt is in fact part of our Korean culture that a mother would always feed her new born on seaweed energized milkOur mission now is to awaken the world to the multitude of benefits of top quality seaweed lifestyle and cultureSeaweed is an environmentally friendly plant based foodWe could not believe the absence of choice out there when it comes to seaweed products maybe we were a little nai vebut decided to stop talking about it and fill the gap in the marketHEASANa Korean word which describes the taking of goodness from the oceans and goodness from the mountainsIt is with this in mind that we offer our seaweed lifestyle and culture to the worldWe never compromise on the quality of any of our seaweed productsIf a product does not meet our highest standardswe won t market itPeriodOnly goodness in HEASAN s productsChiwon EunseoPhotoeva oasis

Seaweed is the ultimate in plantbased foodHEALTHY BENEFITS OF GIM roasted seaweed 1High in iodineRoasted Gimseaweed or any type of seaweed for that matteris a rich source of iodineIodine is a mineral that is essential for your metabolism and helps your thyroid gland to function the way it should beOne sheet of gim contains around half of the daily recommended intake of iodine 2Source of vitamin B12Vitamin B12 supports normal functioning of the brain and nervous system and helps form red blood cellsGim contains 1 2 mg vitamin B12 per 1 sheet 3High in potassiumPotassium is a mineral that helps lower your blood pressure and lowers your risk of stroke and heart diseaseGim contains 50 mg of potassium per 1 sheet 4Contains protein and fiberWhile the amounts are not super highroasted seaweed does actually contain protein and fiber 5Low in calories and saturated fatRoasted seaweed is incredibly low in calories with one sheet containing only 5 calories or lessThe amount of fat in gim is almost negligible 6Delicious tasteOkay this may not necessarily be a health benefitbut the delicious taste of roasted seaweed makes it so much easier to eat as a healthy afternoon snackThe taste is very unique and is hard to compare with anything else It s worth mentioning that roasted seaweed chips are also a very good source of calciumphosphorusmagnesium and vitamin C seaweedsnackohmygimomgplantbasedlunchsnackseavegetableseaveggiesveganhandyfoodfoodwhimsypictureperfectsharingsavourysnacknewraw glutenfreemonocleketodietmediterraneandietmemeskidsnacksnackingwellposhpremixtravelsnacksgimhealthforallqualitysnackorganicsnackpremiumsnacksnackingwellschoolsnacksgourmetsnacks

What is SeaweedSeaweedsa marine form of algaeare found in all the earth s oceanin all climate zones from the warm seas of the tropics to the cold waters of the Arctic and Antarcticyet they remain something of a mysteryThe global distribution of seaweeds has not been comprehensively mappedthe full details of their habitats are unknowntheir taxonomic classification is incomplete and their biodiversity is not yet understoodBut there are reckoned to be about 10 000 kinds of seaweed in the worldand they are essential to the life of the planetAlthough we think the oxygen we breathe comes from land plantsmarine algae of all sizes provide some 75 percent of the planet s oxygen supply through photosynthesisand absorb a huge amount of atmospheric carbon dioxideAnd as noted by Darwinseaweeds play a foundation role in marine ecosystemsproviding food and shelter for many marine organisms and for the people and animals that live on themSee Global Seaweed NetworkNatural History Museumwww nhm ac ukThe Aquatic Biomewww ucmp berkeley eduwww microbeworld

Plantbased revolutionThe growing popularity of a plantbased diet is the most important food trend in 2019Due to rising awareness of the cost of eating too many animalbased foodsconsumers are converting to plantbased foodsSeaweed is the ultimate in plantbased foodHEALTHY BENEFITS OF GIM roasted seaweed 1High in iodineRoasted Gimseaweed or any type of seaweed for that matteris a rich source of iodineIodine is a mineral that is essential for your metabolism and helps your thyroid gland to function the way it should beOne sheet of gim contains around half of the daily recommended intake of iodine 2Source of vitamin B12Vitamin B12 supports normal functioning of the brain and nervous system and helps form red blood cellsGim contains 1 2 mg vitamin B12 per 1 sheet 3High in potassiumPotassium is a mineral that helps lower your blood pressure and lowers your risk of stroke and heart diseaseGim contains 50 mg of potassium per 1 sheet 4Contains protein and fiberWhile the amounts are not super highroasted seaweed does actually contain protein and fiber 5Low in calories and saturated fatRoasted seaweed is incredibly low in calories with one sheet containing only 5 calories or lessThe amount of fat in gim is almost negligible 6Delicious tasteOkay this may not necessarily be a health benefitbut the delicious taste of roasted seaweed makes it so much easier to eat as a healthy afternoon snackThe taste is very unique and is hard to compare with anything else It s worth mentioning that roasted seaweed chips are also a very good source of calciumphosphorusmagnesium and vitamin C

Seaweed is the ultimate in plantbased foodHEALTHY BENEFITS OF GIM roasted seaweed 1High in iodineRoasted Gimseaweed or any type of seaweed for that matteris a rich source of iodineIodine is a mineral that is essential for your metabolism and helps your thyroid gland to function the way it should beOne sheet of gim contains around half of the daily recommended intake of iodine 2Source of vitamin B12Vitamin B12 supports normal functioning of the brain and nervous system and helps form red blood cellsGim contains 1 2 mg vitamin B12 per 1 sheet 3High in potassiumPotassium is a mineral that helps lower your blood pressure and lowers your risk of stroke and heart diseaseGim contains 50 mg of potassium per 1 sheet 4Contains protein and fiberWhile the amounts are not super highroasted seaweed does actually contain protein and fiber 5Low in calories and saturated fatRoasted seaweed is incredibly low in calories with one sheet containing only 5 calories or lessThe amount of fat in gim is almost negligible 6Delicious tasteOkay this may not necessarily be a health benefitbut the delicious taste of roasted seaweed makes it so much easier to eat as a healthy afternoon snackThe taste is very unique and is hard to compare with anything else It s worth mentioning that roasted seaweed chips are also a very good source of calciumphosphorusmagnesium and vitamin C

Let us take you on a journey into the world ofseamoss The specimen you can see in this photo is not one that we would choose to supply to youIt does come from a good area and a farm that has reputable certificationbut look closelyCan you see the little nodule looking parts on this They are a form of scaring caused by fish eating the little ends on thethallusNowthis doesn t mean the product is fakeor has less value from a mineral or nutritional perspectiveIt simply means that it won t look as nice if used as a wholefood ingredient in a salad Take a look at the next few shoots and you ll see what a specimen looks like that has had minimal fish feeding take placeThese are all grown inenvironmentallysustainable farmswhereresponsiblefarming techniques have been appliedThis is more a point on aestheticsI ve had people say this is fake sea moss because of the nodulesIt s notIt s the real dealjust not as pretty We plan to work with this particular Seaweed Farmer you help them devise a way to keep the fish from eating their sea mossIt will be exciting to see what kind of outcome we can help them reach

Seaweed is the ultimate in plantbased foodHEALTHY BENEFITS OF GIM roasted seaweed 1High in iodineRoasted Gimseaweed or any type of seaweed for that matteris a rich source of iodineIodine is a mineral that is essential for your metabolism and helps your thyroid gland to function the way it should beOne sheet of gim contains around half of the daily recommended intake of iodine 2Source of vitamin B12Vitamin B12 supports normal functioning of the brain and nervous system and helps form red blood cellsGim contains 1 2 mg vitamin B12 per 1 sheet 3High in potassiumPotassium is a mineral that helps lower your blood pressure and lowers your risk of stroke and heart diseaseGim contains 50 mg of potassium per 1 sheet 4Contains protein and fiberWhile the amounts are not super highroasted seaweed does actually contain protein and fiber 5Low in calories and saturated fatRoasted seaweed is incredibly low in calories with one sheet containing only 5 calories or lessThe amount of fat in gim is almost negligible 6Delicious tasteOkay this may not necessarily be a health benefitbut the delicious taste of roasted seaweed makes it so much easier to eat as a healthy afternoon snackThe taste is very unique and is hard to compare with anything else It s worth mentioning that roasted seaweed chips are also a very good source of calciumphosphorusmagnesium and vitamin C

What is Seaweed Seaweedsa marine form of algaeare found in all the earth s oceanin all climate zones from the warm seas of the tropics to the cold waters of the Arctic and Antarcticyet they remain something of a mysteryThe global distribution of seaweeds has not been comprehensively mappedthe full details of their habitats are unknowntheir taxonomic classification is incomplete and their biodiversity is not yet understoodBut there are reckoned to be about 10 000 kinds of seaweed in the worldand they are essential to the life of the planetAlthough we think the oxygen we breathe comes from land plantsmarine algae of all sizes provide some 75 percent of the planet s oxygen supply through photosynthesisand absorb a huge amount of atmospheric carbon dioxideAnd as noted by Darwinseaweeds play a foundation role in marine ecosystemsproviding food and shelter for many marine organisms and for the people and animals that live on themSee Global Seaweed NetworkNatural History Museumwww nhm ac ukThe Aquatic Biomewww ucmp berkeley eduwww microbeworld org
